,"video_url":"","parts":[{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/keeping-your-pay-tax-records/overview","slug":"overview","order":1,"title":"Overview","body":"<p>You need to keep records if you have to send HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) a Self Assessment tax return.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll need your records to fill in your tax return correctly. If <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> checks your tax return, they may ask for the documents. </p>\n\n<h2>How to keep your records</h2>\n\n<p>There are no rules on how you must keep records. You can keep them on paper, digitally or as part of a software program (like book-keeping software). </p>\n\n<p>If they aren’t accurate, complete and readable, <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> can charge you a penalty.</p>\n\n<h2>Lost or destroyed records</h2>\n\n<p>Try to get copies of as much as you can, eg ask banks for copies of statements, suppliers for duplicate invoice etc.</p>\n\n<p>If you can&rsquo;t recreate all your records, you can use ‘provisional’ or ‘estimated’ figures. You must use the &lsquo;Any other information&rsquo; box on the tax return to say that this is what you&rsquo;re doing.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>‘Provisional’ means you’ll be able to get paperwork to confirm your figures later. ‘Estimated’ means you won’t be able to confirm the figures.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If your figures turn out to be wrong and you haven’t paid enough tax, you may have to pay interest and penalties.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/keeping-your-pay-tax-records/how-long-to-keep-your-records","slug":"how-long-to-keep-your-records","order":2,"title":"How long to keep your records","body":"<p>How long you need to keep your records depends on whether:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you&rsquo;re self-employed or not</li>\n  <li>you sent your tax return before or after the deadline</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Self-employed sole trader, business partnership or partner</h3>\n\n<p>If you sent your tax return on or before the 31 January deadline, you must keep your records for at least 5 years and 10 months after the end of the tax year the tax return is for.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong> </p>\n\n<p>If you send your 2011 to 2012 tax return by 31 January 2013, you must keep your records until at least the end of January 2018.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you sent your tax return after the 31 January deadline, you must keep your records for the longer of:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>5 years and 10 months after the end of the tax year the tax return is for</li>\n  <li>15 months after you sent your tax return</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Individuals and anyone else who sends a return</h3>\n\n<p>If you sent your tax return on or before the 31 January deadline, you should keep your records for at least 22 months after the end of the tax year the tax return is for.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong> </p>\n\n<p>If you send your 2011 to 2012 tax return by 31 January 2013, keep your records until at least the end of January 2014.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you sent your tax return after the 31 January deadline, you should keep your records for at least 15 months after you sent it.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/keeping-your-pay-tax-records/employees-and-limited-company-directors","slug":"employees-and-limited-company-directors","order":3,"title":"Employees and limited company directors","body":"<h2>Income from employment</h2>\n\n<p>You should keep documents about your pay and tax, including:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>your P45 - if you leave your job, this shows your pay and tax to the date you left</li>\n  <li>your P60 - if you&rsquo;re in a job on 5 April, this shows your pay and tax for the tax year</li>\n  <li>form P11D - this shows your expenses and benefits, like a company car or health insurance</li>\n  <li>certificates for any Taxed Award Schemes</li>\n  <li>information about any redundancy or ter