ine, you may not get your statement on time to tell you what to pay. </p>\n\n<p>To make sure you pay the right amount of tax you may need to work out your <a href=\"/understand-self-assessment-statement/balancing-payments\" title=\"Balancing payments\">balancing payment</a> and what payments on account you need to make for the next tax year. To do this <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://online.hmrc.gov.uk/login?GAREASONCODE=-1&amp;GARESOURCEID=SaAAll&amp;GAURI=https://online.hmrc.gov.uk/self-assessment/&amp;Reason=-1&amp;APPID=SaAAll&amp;URI=https://online.hmrc.gov.uk/self-assessment/\" title=\"Login and check your Self Assessment statement\">check your tax statement online</a> or look through your tax records. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can <a href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/payinghmrc/selfassessment.htm\" title=\"Pay HMRC\" rel=\"external\">pay HM Revenue &amp; Customs</a> in different ways, including direct debit and internet banking.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/understand-self-assessment-statement/payments-on-account","slug":"payments-on-account","order":2,"title":"Payments on account","body":"<p>&lsquo;Payments on account&rsquo; are advance payments towards the tax bill you&rsquo;ll owe for that tax year. </p>\n\n<p>You usually make them if you send a tax return and the tax due is over £1,000 and 80% or less has been collected at source. For example, through your tax code. </p>\n\n<p>If the payments on account you&rsquo;ve made are higher than your tax bill, HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) will refund you the difference. </p>\n\n<h2>What and when to pay</h2>\n\n<p>Each payment is half your previous year’s tax bill. Your payments are due on 31 January and 31 July. </p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong><br />\nYou’re self-employed and the tax due for 2011 to 2012 tax year is £1,500. For the 2012 to 2013 tax year you make your first payment on account of £750 by 31 January 2013 and your second of £750 by 31 July 2013.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>When you do your tax return online you&rsquo;ll be shown a &lsquo;tax calculation&rsquo; (it&rsquo;s sent to you in the post if you do the return on paper). This tells you the tax due, the next payment on account instalment and when these are to be paid.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong><br />\nYour 2011 to 2012 tax year calculation will show you the tax due for that tax year and the first payment on account for the 2012 to 2013 tax year.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;ve already made some payments on account towards the amount due, these won’t be shown. You can see these on your Self Assessment statement instead. </p>\n\n<h2>How to pay</h2>\n\n<p>You can <a href=\"/pay-self-assessment-tax-bill\" title=\"paying your tax bill\">pay your tax bill</a> in different ways, including direct debit and internet banking.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/understand-self-assessment-statement/change-your-payments-on-account","slug":"change-your-payments-on-account","order":3,"title":"Change your payments on account","body":"<p>You can ask HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) to reduce your payments on account if you know your tax bill is going to be lower than last year. To do this you can either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>log in to your <a href=\"/file-your-self-assessment-tax-return\" title=\"Login to your HMRC online account\"><abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> online account</a> </li>\n  <li>send form SA303 to your local tax office </li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/sa/forms/sa303.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Form SA303, reduce your payments on account' (PDF, 300KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Form SA303, reduce your payments on account’ (PDF, 300KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you end up paying too little, <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</a